<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>🎓 What You Learned — Cookies</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/style.css">
</head>
<body>
  <div class="edu-page">
    <a href="/" class="back-link">← Back to Challenges</a>
    <img src="/images/logo.png" alt="EECS Girls Who Tech Camp" class="page-logo">

    <div class="edu-card">
      <div class="congrats">🍪</div>
      <h1>Challenge 2 Complete!</h1>
      <p style="color:#9090b0; margin-top:5px;">Cookie Monster</p>
      <div class="flag-reveal"><%= flag %></div>
    </div>

    <div class="edu-section">
      <h2>📚 What You Just Learned</h2>
      <p>You explored <strong>browser cookies</strong> — small pieces of data that websites store in your browser. Cookies are used for many purposes: keeping you logged in, remembering your preferences, and tracking your activity.</p>
      <p>You used the browser's <strong>Developer Tools</strong> (<code>F12</code>) to inspect cookies. In the <code>Application</code> tab (Chrome) or <code>Storage</code> tab (Firefox), you can see every cookie a website has set — including its name, value, and expiration date.</p>
      <p>The <code>document.cookie</code> command in the Console gives you quick access to all non-HttpOnly cookies on the current page.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="edu-section">
      <div class="real-world-box">
        <h3>🌍 Real-World Application</h3>
        <p>Cookies are central to web security. <strong>Session hijacking</strong> attacks steal a user's session cookie to impersonate them. That's why important cookies should be marked <code>HttpOnly</code> (can't be read by JavaScript) and <code>Secure</code> (only sent over HTTPS). Understanding cookies is essential for both building and securing web applications.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="career-box">
        <h3>👩‍💻 Career Connection</h3>
        <p><strong>Web Application Security Engineers</strong> design systems to protect cookies and user sessions. They implement security features like <code>HttpOnly</code> flags, <code>SameSite</code> attributes, and secure token rotation. Every major tech company — Google, Meta, Amazon — employs security engineers to protect billions of users' data.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="edu-section">
      <h2>🔑 Key Takeaways</h2>
      <p>1. Cookies store data in your browser that websites can read and write.</p>
      <p>2. Never store sensitive secrets (like passwords) in client-accessible cookies.</p>
      <p>3. The <code>HttpOnly</code> flag prevents JavaScript from reading a cookie, adding a layer of protection.</p>
      <p>4. Developer Tools let you inspect, edit, and delete cookies on any website you visit.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="next-btns">
      <a href="/" class="next-btn secondary">← All Challenges</a>
      <% if (hasNext) { %>
      <a href="/challenge/<%= nextNum %>" class="next-btn">Next Challenge →</a>
      <% } %>
    </div>
  </div>
</body>
</html>
